Map.PNG | map1_size = 300 | map1_caption = Location of the mouth of the Dungeness River in Washington | map1_locator = Washington <!-- *** Websites *** --> | commons = }} The '''Dungeness River''' is a {{convert|28|mi|km|adj=on}} long<ref name=gnis>{{GNIS|1528593|Dungeness River}}</ref> river located in the [[Olympic Peninsula]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]]. It rises near [[Mount Constance]] in the [[Olympic Mountains]] within the [[Olympic National Park]], flows through the [[Buckhorn Wilderness]], passes by the town of [[Sequim, Washington|Sequim]], and empties into the [[Strait of Juan de Fuca]] at [[Dungeness Bay]], behind the [[Dungeness Spit]].<ref>{{GNIS|1519006|Dungeness Bay}}</ref> One of its main tributaries is the [[Gray Wolf River]]. The river was named for Dungeness Spit. The name "Dungeness" refers to the [[Dungeness (headland)|Dungeness]] headland in [[England]]. It was given by [[George Vancouver]] in 1792, who wrote: ''The low sandy point of land, which from its great resemblance to Dungeness in the British Channel, I called New Dungeness.''<ref>{{cite book |last= Phillips |first= James W. |title= Washington State Place Names |year= 1971 |publisher= University of Washington Press |isbn= 0-295-95158-3}}</ref> ==See also== *[[List of Washington rivers]] *[[Dungeness crab]] ==References== {{reflist}} [[Category:Rivers of Washington (state)]] [[Category:Landforms of Clallam County, Washington]] [[Category:Landforms of Jefferson County, Washington]] {{ClallamWA-geo-stub}} {{JeffersonWA-geo-stub}}
